description.text:
I saw some problems with the originals, so here's my fix.
Changes:
• It's all one part. No assembly screws, and a nice big open space for accessing the single fixture screw.
• It fits the two types of dust filters on Thingiverse (the unit with two screws as well as the taller threaded version that I use).
• Vertical structure has added support ribs - even with 20% infill this seems to be more than stable enough, keeping the part lighter.
• Rear wire harness retainer is now intended to be a zip tie, not a separate printed part. I'd like to eliminate an extra part entirely.
• Prints without supports. I'd like to:
• Have the wire loom retainer be built in.
• Make the filament dust filters swap out a little easier. Mine are a press fit so some improvement might be seen modding the filter itself.
• Fix the unit so that when it's bolted up it cannot rotate freely.

Printed around 25% infill at 0.20 layer height in PLA.
No real instructions other than bolt it on and enjoy.

title: Beta Precision Piezo/Moriquendi E3D Titan and Titan Aero Piezo Z probe Bracket

description.text:
PLEASE NOTE: IF YOU HAVE BEEN REDIRECTED HERE FROM ALIEXPRESS OR ANY OTHER VENDOR OF THESE PRODUCTS OTHER THAN http://www.precisionpiezo.co.uk PLEASE BE AWARE THAT THEIR CLONES OF OUR PRODUCT ARE LESS LIKELY TO WORK, WILL NOT BE SUPPORTED BY US AND BUYING THEM WILL REDUCE OUR ABILITY TO DESIGN NEW PRODUCTS FOR THE REPRAP COMMUNITY.

PLEASE MAKE ONE YOURSELF OR BUY GENUINE.

Update 18-08-17 a 27mm piezo version has been made by m1n1m - many thanks.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2490018

Precision Piezo and Moriquendi present a solution for piezo z probing using titan and titan aero hotends/extruders.

Print the bracket in ABS (mouse ears are included for adhesion cut them off afterwards).

Bond using superglue (cyanoacrylate) a 20mm piezo disc, brass side down towards the bracket, into the recess in the base. Please use 2-4 drops of glue, on the underside of the disc only, preferably keeping it to the front and back of the disc to allow the disc to bend with the bracket. Do not over-glue it! Attach to a piezo probing board such as available at http://www.precisionpiezo.co.uk.

This has been tested but we are calling it beta for now, please feed back to us at http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?1,767998,page=5 with any improvements.

You might want to alter the mounting holes in the base to suit your setup.

It should be possible to attach other hotends to this bracket.

The titan mount bracket spacer allows it to work if used upside down, you don't need it if it is orientated as it is shown here.

comments.text: Pardon my ignorance but I how do these work. I understand the one that fits to the top of the groove mount, the pressure from the nozzle touching the bed, squashes the piezo which produces a voltage. How do they work when the piezo is mounted to the titan bracket?
comments.author: totalitarian

comments.text: Piezos generate a detectable voltage rise, when tapped, squeezed or bent. In the Piezo20 module design https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2319993 the disc is supported on its periphery and it gets bent by the hotend pushing up into the centre from below. In the titan bracket, the piezo is bonded with superglue/CA glue to the base, but the shape of the base means the piezo gets bent when the bracket is pushed upwards by the hotend contacting the bed. It's not quite as easy to tune, as the force transmitted is less direct than in the above-the-hotend implemntation, but it does work. Don't overdo the glue just a thin smear around the underside of the piezo disc. Hope this helps.

title: Da Vinci 1.0 Top Door Hardware Kit

description.text:
Hardware kit to add a top door opening to a Da Vinci 1.0 and other models using the same housing design. This really improves your view of the print bed and parts as they are printing on the machine.

Uses approximately a 12" x 5-3/4" x 1/4" (305 x 145 x 6mm) piece of clear acrylic or Lexan for the door. Uses ten M4x12 button-head machine screws and nuts for mounting.

<<Caution - be careful if you have small children, this modification allows access to the machine internals without triggering the lid switch, if you are still using the lid switch.>>

Printer:

XYZ Da Vinci 1.0A Hacked with E3D V6 and Repetier V92

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3mm layers

Infill:

Solid works best

Notes:

Print 1 copy of the hinge file and a second mirrored in your slicer for the opposite side.

Hinges are print-in-place joints that print as one piece.

PLA or ABS works fine.

<<Be Careful - This mod requires you to disassemble your printer and the connection to the control panel. I've done this several times on my machine without a problem but move slowly and carefully.>>

Remove the side panels of your machine with a plastic spatula. Carefully remove the top-front panel and carefully loosen the tape and glue that holds the ribbon cable in place. Slip the ziff-connector out of the front display. Remove or tape over the the display/circuit board to protect it. Cut an opening approximately 12-1/8" x 5-7/8" (approx. 308 x 129mm).

Cut a piece of clear acrylic slightly smaller than your hole approximately 12" x 5-3/4" x 1/4" (305 x 145 x 6mm). Match-drill clearance holes approx. 0.188" (4mm) diameter for all screws. Install all the parts. Reinstall the top-front panel.

I made this mod to my Da Vinci 1.0A, for other models there may be additional steps or safeguards required. Go slow and pay close attention and you should be good. If you have kids, it's nice to have a small step stool by the printer so they can look in the top through the new clear door.

Good luck! If you use these parts and make the mod to your printer please post a "Make".

You may also be interested in my Da Vinci Cable Carrier Chain Mount.

title: Spring loaded bracket for glass plate

description.text:
These brackets are made and modeled on a 3 mm glass bed. I had a lot of issues regarding the bed which was moving due to the thermal expansion of the aluminum underneath, so any calibration was impossible. Standard brackets are great for PLA, but if you mostly print ABS like me they are totally useless. Moreover, the knobs after just an hour of printing were totally untightened because of the heat.
I made these spring loaded brackets that should keep the glass bed from moving away and (in theory) should not have any calibration issues. So far I'm pleased with the result.
My suggestion is to print with ABS; make two of them and on the opposite corner put a standard bracket.
Made for a FF creator pro but should be OK for any bed that has corner screws; the spring used is a standard pen spring (3mmx18mm).
Cheers

Edit 6/30/2017: Don't leaf your stencils all over the place - organize them with my new stencil holder!

Edit 6/29/2017: I've created a new stencil of a butterfly, with a new handle design! All new stencils going forward will have this improved design, and I will retrofit all previous stencils shortly....

--End of Edits--

Ahh GlaDOS. She's evil, she's in the game Portal, and she sometimes reminds us to appreciate the great outdoors:

Enjoy this next test. I'm going to go to the surface. It's a beautiful day out. Yesterday I saw a deer. If you solve this next test, maybe I'll let you ride an elevator all the way up to the break room, and I'll tell you about the time I saw a deer again.

...from indoors. Yes, that's right. It's time for a new stencil!

Today, it's a leaf. This can be a leaf from any season you'd like, just use your imagination.

My favorite type of leaf is from fall, or autumn as it's also called. But the type of leaf is really just a state of mind. Do you like spring, when all the leaves are little baby things, just popping out? Or perhaps summer, when the drought hits and they're big but shriveled? In winter, most leaves are just dead, empty husks, but in autumn, they're pretty and dying. Dying just for you, to appreciate their beautiful splendor. Green? Pshaw! Try yellow, red, orange, brown, AND green. Colors!

You can print this stencil in so many different colors, but it won't matter. Because the only person who will see this stencil is you. What others will see, if you make coffee for them, is the result of the stencil: powder lovingly sifted into place, in the shape of a leaf! And because this is more of a symbolic leaf, you, and the appreciator of the leaf, can decide what you want this leaf to be. What you want it to represent. And more importantly, what you want it to consist of. Cinnamon? Check! Powdered sugar? Yum! Pie spice? Of course! In fact, pretty much anything powdered can be sifted through this stencil, and it will continue to happily do it's job. Cumin? Wow! Curry? Spicy! Yup, just about anything.

If you're sick of leaves, don't worry, there are other stencils:

https://flic.kr/p/5osyYD

Stay tuned for more stencils and, don't forget, these can be totally used anywhere, anytime, for any reason! Think about it: cupcakes, cakes, pie...I mean, you can sprinkle stuff all over the place, right? Go forth and sift powdery substances!

Super important note: Although this prints easily, the little center part of the leaf is very fragile! Let the part cool all the way before attempting to remove this from the bed. Also, try to use a longer part removal tool, and really get in there, all the way around, gently. Depending on how you orient this on the bed, the "point" could be in any direction. It's probably better to have the point facing up, but that's just me! Otherwise, a fairly simple print.

How to Use

It's easy to use a stencil, but here's a video that will show you how:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M8ugnBwyCgk

If you're like me, and prefer text, here's some directions I wrote:

1) Put coffee in vessel
2) Shake up your creamer a lot, so it's bubbly
3) Pour creamer over coffee slowly, so it stays at the top (don't stir!)
4) Leave very little "headroom" at the top - maybe 1/4" or less?
5) Place stencil over the top of the vessel
6) Lightly sprinkle the powder of your choice over the top of the stencil

I like to make sure I sprinkle over the entire stencil, that way I know I'm getting into all the nooks and crannies.

As far as sprinkling goes, I love using little metal mesh teabag balls. They're easy to fill, and do a good job of sifting most powders you'll be using.

Fusion 360 and Simplify3D

Fusion 360 is an awesome tool, and I use it for all of my 3D design because it's parametric, and lets me set things up once (like a template), and then have different versions with different attributes. They've been adding a lot of new features recently, like folders within folders, copying between different projects, and some other third thing. Always new!

I use Simplify3D to slice and prepare for print because, although it costs money, you get what you pay for, and this program is perfect for my needs.

title: Connecting Rod Bottle opener split pattern for sand casting

description.text:
I made this sand cast connecting rod bottle opener.

This part is a split pattern for sand casting, it has a minimum of 5 degrees of draft on all surfaces to aid removal from sand molds. It should be printed in duplicate, and assembled with 2.5x6mm pins in the far holes.

I have reduced the gap between the opening blades to 15mm to improve function. the pictured pattern and castings have a 20mm gap, which is too wide and can grip the glass lip of the bottle.

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 layers or finer

Notes:

The finer the layer lines and print quality, the less hand work will be needed to Finnish the pattern

Preparing the split pattern

I filed and sanded as many of the surfaces as smooth as I could get them to aid in releasing from the sand.

I drilled the far pair of holes to 2.5mm, and used a 2.5mm by 6mm dowl pin to align the halves. Use a drill press with the belt removed and spin the chuck by hand, you want the holes as perpindicular as posible, but you don't want to over drill or distort the hole with the speed of a running drill press.

I found grinding the exposed portion of the pins to a slight taper helped the ease of assembly and release of the two halves.

I used 2.5mm thread forming screws in the inner pair of holes to pull the pattern out of the sand.

After that, they are ready to be sand cast.

I designed this in OnShape. I prefer Fusion360, but OnShape works on Linux.

comments.text: You should not connect directly to the flat bar as that bypasses the fuse and can allow your equipment to draw too much current. Install a fuse and then simply install a female/female spade jumper from the the two "hot" connections on the two spade contacts opposite the flat bar up to two of the spade contacts on the switch (either the two connections together with a plastic bar in between or the two farther apart to avoid short circuits). You can then tap the common from the bottom spade on the socket assembly and the two power lines from the other two spades on the switch, while also keeping the fuse in to prevent overloading your equipment.

title: Anet A8 sliding lateral spool stand

description.text:
Hi folks ! This is my attempt to have a compact setting. Instead of having the spool stand on top of the printer (BTW, this is a bad idea as this contributes to unwanted vibrations and stresses a bit the frame), the idea is to have it positioned as low as possible, and preferably without the need of any frame modification. So this spool stand simply slides on the right side of the printer's frame, (close to the Power Unit). Instantly installed and removed, no screws & no bolts needed. Moreover, the design mimics the look of the frame ridifier I love so much for it's efficiency : https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2074478/#made.
Just print as well an additional spool holder like : https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:127181, screw inside the hole the rod (can be shortened) and you're ready to go !

description.text:
This is a camera mount for a 5.5mm Borescope/Endoscopic USB Camera for the Printrbot Play. This camera mount fits on the back of the Extruder. The USB Camera rides along with the Extruder as it is printing so you can get a good view of what is happening with the 3D print.

This part has an open slot down one side and 4 circular holes from top to bottom along the
length of the shaft to improve air flow to the USB Camera. When the LED lights are on the camera will get warm and generate heat depending on the brightness level of the LED lights.

Watching the 3D printing process up close on a large screen monitor makes things more interesting. Borescope/Endoscopic USB Cameras can be found at a low cost by searching the Internet. You can use Free WebCam software packages to view video generated by the USB Borescope/Endoscopic Camera.

This part was designed using the Free version of the eMachineShop Software Package.

title: LED Light & Spool Holder for Prusa i3

description.text:
I’ve been really pleased with my ‘Improved Prusa Spool Holder’ (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2395279) but after a couple of months I realised I needed something else... I also wanted a light to do justice to my timelapses so I went back to the drawing board to combine the Spool holder with an led light and after a couple of months use and some design improvements it’s now ready for all you Prusa i3 users out there!

You can see my complete showcase and 'how to' youtube video here;-
https://youtu.be/UoFhU1OZtQo

As with the improved spool holder I’ve done away with having to detach the arms each time you change a spool and I’ve incorporated a removable spool spindle that easily locks in with a satisfying snap!
It’s simple to put together so if you can solder a wire and use a hacksaw then you’ll find this a piece of cake… even better, the parts cost under $10 which is awesome given the results. I’ve included links to the parts in the description.

My other designs (including the spool holder) can be found here:-
https://www.thingiverse.com/ScottyMakesStuff/designs

You can see my other DIY videos on my youtube channel 'Scotty Makes Stuff' here:-
https://www.youtube.com/channel/UChDeVchB6CCF--0wQQYNIhQ

A 12V LED strip,

comments.author: ScottyMakesStuff

comments.text: There's lots of ways to calibrate your 3d printer...  just google it?  you really need to do it for every filament you use. I use a 2cm cube and slice it with no fill, 2 bottom layers, 0 top layers and 1 perimeter. Print it and you get 2 things from it. Using vernier calipers measure the wall thickness of the top most layers. If it's wider than your extrusion width then you're over extruding and you need to reduce the extrusion multiplier. You can also measure the outside box dimensions to see if your printer prints a square as a slightly rectangular shape. But your Prusa should be very close to 20mm +-0.1mm as they're good machines.

title: Customizable Jack Screw to adjust height of Corners on MPCNC
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Update 6/27/2017
I added JackScrew_Test_Rev30.stl and & JackScrewMate_Test0?mmClear_Rev30.stl. The ? in the 2nd name denotes the clearance amount for the internal threads. The bottom & top flex corners I uploaded are .4mm clearance, so try the test prints 1st which should take considerably less time to print to make sure this design will work for you. I added the following variable:
Clearance = 0.4; //clearance to add to Thread OD for internal Threads
to the bottom, top & Lock-CornerC openscad files.

I have been looking for an easier way to adjust the level of my corners & came across this idea: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:953976 . The problem was I wanted to use my same corner styles. I did this design in openscad & my biggest problem was finding a screw thread library that had some flexibility. Since I am not using a print cooling fan, the standard 30 degree angle of threads do not print very well for me. I found this library that gives me the flexibility needed, http://dkprojects.net/openscad-threads/ . After some trial & error prints, a thread angle of 40 degrees and a thread pitch of 4 worked for me although the internal threads for the bottom parts are not always coming out clean. There is an image showing all my trial & error parts.

After playing with some of the printed threaded parts, I thought it might be more useful to make the middle screw shaft a Jack Screw instead. I was originally calling this a turnbuckle, but after some research on the Internet, looked like it should be called a Jack Screw. It is probably a stronger connection with the original design with that shaft resting at the bottom, but I am going to try this as it should not be more than 4mm off the bottom. There is an option in the openscad file to do it either way. I included 3 STL JackScrew version lengths with that option as well as a Flex Foot Bottom for it to fit in. The Jack Screw is hollowed out thru the center to allow the insertion of a 1/2" EMT pipe. If you make this Jack Screw very high, you might want to use that option to make it stronger. I left a 1mm base at the bottom of the Jack Screw for the EMT to rest on, but that is changable with a variable in the openscad file. I added an access hole to the bottom of the Jack Screw to make it easier to get the pipe out if you needed to. Having that pipe inside Jack Screw will also make the allen wrench access hole unusable unless you drill thru the pipe.

I did not include the thread library as he using the GNU public license & the MPCNC uses a different license, so i kept the license the same as the MPCNC. You can easily download that file from: http://dkprojects.net/openscad-threads/threads.scad & change the function segments which is currently line 65 to:

function segments (diameter) = (round(((diameter 3.14) / 4) / 1) 4; //The number 1 should be close to 1mm segments. The reason I have the 4 in there twice is to give me a vertex point on each quadrant. I also created a threadsRough.scad which has a 3 instead of the 1 so it does not take so long to render while I was designing this. I contacted the author of the thread library & he is going to add an option for resolution.

I have included several different height Jack Screw STL files. I initially used 85mm height for testing, but am using the 100mm length. I am using the corners from the previous design. 88mm is probably the minium height you should use.

I included a modified version of the Lock-CornerC STL & openscad source, but they currently are untested. I made 2 different heights for those as I was not sure 27mm was enough height if you are using this Jack Screw. There is a 27mm & 40mm height version & a mirrored one of each. The mirroring of the part had to be done before cutting the threads, so I have that option in the openscad file. I did not make a 25mm or 25.4mm version of that lock, but if someone needs one, I will take a look at creating those also.

For adjusting the Jack Screw, I included a 32mm plastic wrench & a couple of different style thumbwheels. You can also use a 5mm allen wrench if you do not add the 1/2" EMT to the middle of the Jack Screw. The thumbwheel I moddified from:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:225188

I will add a remix of that separately after I have all these files uploaded. The wrench worked best for me. This is probably obvious, but if you use the thumbwheels, you will have to make one for each corner & install it on the Jack Screw before installing the bottom & top parts. There is a lip on the thumbwheels to keep it from dropping below the adjustment nut.

I included an image of the variables you can change with the JackScrew_Rev30.scad file as well as a few pictures on the printed parts.

I have only installed one corner, but that seems to work pretty good so far. I should be able to start cutting again in a couple of days.

description.text: This is a small handle sized to accept a Harbor Freight magnetic bit holder and turn it into a pocket sized screwdriver. It uses standard 1/4" hex bits available from most hardware, building supply and tool stores.

Notes:

This is my first ever design for 3d printing. I used Tinkercad, and after a lot of trial and error was finally able to get the holes sized correctly for the bit holder.

The actual printing was done by importing the STL file to Cura, then printed on the library's TAZ4 printer. The printing parameters are as follows:
Infill: 50%
Resolution: 3
Shells: 3

Next time I will probably use 80% infill so I get a more rugged handle. As it is, it works very well for light use, however, I want it to be durable enough to loosen tight screws without breaking.

I started by creating a cylinder slightly smaller than the diameter of the handle I wanted. Then I took three rectangular columns slightly wider than the handle's diameter and of the same height as the cylinder, rotated each one slightly and merged them with the cylinder. This gave me the flutes on the handle. Next I created tapered cylinders and attached them to the top and bottom of the handle.

Creating the holes was the hardest part because for some reason Tinkercad's measurements didn't print to the exact size. I printed disks with various diameter holes until I got two that were close enough to make the design work. I ended up using a circular hole measuring 10.91 mm and a hexagonal hole of 7.98 mm.

Since the entire bit holder is 2-7/8 inches long, I made the length of the handle just under 2-1/4 inches so the entire finished length is 3-1/4 inches without a bit. The diameter of the handle is about 5/8 of an inch.

Construction Tips

The bit holder fits slightly loose, so it needs to be glued to the handle. I used 5 minute Epoxy to keep the handle and the bit holder together. When I get time, I plan on dipping the handle in liquid rubber to give it a stickier grip.

When I glued the handle to the bit holder, I had to clamp the pieces in a vice because the epoxy trapped air bubbles and the pressure tried to force the bit holder from the handle. By clamping the handle, I was able to get a good bond, and the air bubbles were forced out. It created a little bit of a mess, but a quick wipe with a paper towel took care of the excess glue.

In future versions I may put a small hole in the bottom to relieve the pressure.

My Journey to Create the Perfect Pocket Sized Screwdriver

In 1991 I bought a small magnetic bit screwdriver from Sears, and used it until I lost it this year. Since that model of screwdriver is no longer available except on eBay for $50, I decided to make my own.

I started by downloading various handles from Thingiverse, however none of the handles were exactly what I was looking for. They were either too large in diameter, or too short, or the bit holder wouldn't fit.

Because of this, I decided to design my own. I opened an account at Tinkercad and started learning how to design in 3d.

I purchased a magnetic bit holder (item #62692) from Harbor Freight for $1.99, and designed the handle around the bit holder's dimensions. The round part of the bit holder is 3/8 of an inch in diameter, and the hexagonal part is 1/4 of an inch. After printing multiple test holes, I merged the correctly sized holes and centered them in the handle. I left 1/4 inch at the bottom so the metal end would be covered. I may extend the hole through the bottom of the handle next time to make a slightly shorter version. The hole would also have the benefit of preventing the trapping of air bubbles when it gets glued up.

It will fit in an Altoids tin with room to spare for extra bits.

Please feel free to print copies and if you make changes, I would appreciate you crediting me with this original design.

Special Thanks to the Pikes Peak Library District in Colorado Springs, Colorado!

When I started looking for handles to print, I needed a place to print them because I don't own a 3d printer. My local Library District has a makerspace, so I worked with the great staff members there to make this a reality. I highly recommend the PPLD Makerspace because they have friendly, knowledgeable staff members, and they really enjoy working with people who use the makerspace.

If you live in the Colorado Springs area, visit Library 21c and check it out.
Here are the links to their websites:
https://ppld.org/library-21c
https://ppld.org/c3/makerspaces

description.text:
I had a couple of these bare USB webcams sitting in a box for a project that's not ready to get started, and I needed a webcam to record some live video. The bare design of the ELP cameras are great because there's no trendy curvy plastic shell around them, but there's also not an easy way to just have them sit on a table. The screw mount holes are also 2mm, which I do not have and can't just go buy at the hardware store.

Solution? Lock the camera PCB into a slot and put a tripod mount on it. I have plenty of tripods for reasons I don't want to publicly discuss. This also opens it up to using all sorts of tripody mounts, like those bendy gripper guys, or the teensy $1 wire leg tripods from eBay.

This fits any camera with a ~38mm wide PCB no more than 1.8mm thick and no obstructions in the first 3mm of the bottom of the PCB. There is an additional backoff of 2.6mm for components placed on the back of the PCB which is more than generous. Tested with:

  • ELP-USBFHD01M-XXX "Full 1080P" (OV2710 sensor)
  • ELP-USB100W03M-XXX "720P" (OV9712 sensor)

Note that the blue painter's tape in the photos is there to protect it from shorting out against metal bits before I made this tripod mount and is not structural or required by this mount in any way. The stabilizing brace mounts the camera board very securely and also keeps the 1/4" nut from coming out when a tripod is not attached.

description.text:
Updated 2017.7.4 to curve/carve out some bits unneeded plastic, and widen the large screwdriver holes slightly. As the latest photo shows, went through a few iterations. Bought a new set of screwdrivers to replace those missing, and still have an excess of holders. :)

Also, this was a first of a series: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2418948

Screwdriver holder for pegboard. Pictures of one and two holders mounted on my pegboard. Also discovered today that most of my screwdrivers have somehow (hint: kids) gone missing, as the picture has all the screwdrivers I could find in my toolboxes. Ordered a new set...

Goals:

  • Use with common (in the USA) pegboard with 1/4" holes on 1" spacing.
  • Can use common drywall screws (or any "wood" screw with ~4mm outside diameter).
  • Does not damage the pegboard.
  • Anchors should be somewhat re-usable.
  • Very solid mount with screw/anchor together.
  • Allow for differing alignment by 1/2 grid space horizontal (thus four holes in the holder).
  • Easy to keep clean (no complex exposed surfaces).
  • Very (very) solid!

Note the print in the picture was meant to be fast, not pretty - so printed with 0.3mm layers at 150mm/s (the upper limit for my printer). Printed with 20% infill (more than enough), so the object is almost 80% air. The result is good enough for my purpose. :)

There are four screw-holes in the holder. You will use only two. Which two depends on the horizontal placement wanted.

Using at present 1.5in coarse thread drywall screws (as I had a box of screws). This is not remotely a precise requirement. :) The screw needs to be long enough to pass through the part, and into the anchor. The screw can be longer, if there is clearance behind the pegboard. Finer threads are no problem, as long as you do not over torque the screws. Easy to drive with a simple manual screwdriver. (Very easy to over-torque with a power tool.)

The trickiest part of this design was the anchors, and I am satisfied with the result.

The safety pins on the Splatmaster Z200 are quite sensitive to breakage on the safe side.

This thing is intended as a drop-in replacement. I've tried ABS and PLA. PLA gives the best functioning part, as the friction is lower.

You'll need to add o-rings, so the pin keeps its position.

  • For the hot side: od=7mm, id=4mm, thickness=1.5mm
  • for the safe side: od=6mm; id=3mm, thickness=1.5mm

I found that the part works fine without the o-rings as well, so I also added versions without the o-ring groove, these parts should be more durable, as they lack the weak spot the original part had.
